Babassu nuts have a reputation for being the hardest nut on Earth. Babassu palms grow along the southern and eastern fringe of Brazilian Amazonia in poorly developed provinces such as Maranhão, occupying almost 29 million hectares. For many the babassu palm is considered the 'tree of life', providing an extremely important source of products and income, mainly from its fruit. Flour, animal feed, medicines and beverages can all be produced from the fruit, while the seeds contain oil useful for cooking and soap-making. Even the leaves provide thatch for houses and can be woven into mats for constructing house walls, while stems are used for timbers.